    <h2>What is Blood Pressure (BP)?</h2>
    <p>
      When you turn on a tap at home, water flows because of pressure in the pipes. 
      Your heart works in a very similar way—it pumps blood with a certain pressure 
      through your body’s “pipes,” called blood vessels. This is what we call blood pressure (BP).
    </p>

    <h3>Every BP Reading Has Two Numbers:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Systolic (upper number):</strong> the pressure when your heart squeezes blood out.</li>
      <li><strong>Diastolic (lower number):</strong> the pressure when your heart relaxes and refills.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>A normal value is around <strong>120/80 mm Hg</strong>.</p>

    <h3>Why High BP is Dangerous</h3>
    <p>
      High blood pressure (hypertension) is often called a “silent killer.” 
      You may feel fine, but inside, your arteries and heart are under constant stress. Over time, this can:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Damage blood vessels</li>
      <li>Make your heart work harder and grow weak</li>
      <li>Lead to heart attacks, strokes, kidney problems, or even sudden death</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Why Low BP Matters Too</h3>
    <p>Low blood pressure (hypotension) means your organs don’t get enough blood. This can cause:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Dizziness</li>
      <li>Fainting</li>
      <li>Weakness</li>
    </ul>
    <p> In severe cases, it can even be life-threatening.</p>

    <h3>Keeping BP in the Safe Zone</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Normal:</strong> around 120/80 mm Hg</li>
      <li><strong>High:</strong> 130/80 or above</li>
      <li><strong>Low:</strong> below 90/60</li>
    </ul>

    <p>You can protect yourself by:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Checking BP regularly</li>
      <li>Staying active (even 5 extra minutes of walking or climbing stairs daily helps)</li>
      <li>Eating wisely (less salt, more fruits, vegetables, and potassium-rich foods like bananas)</li>
      <li>Sleeping well and managing stress</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Final Thought</h3>
    <p>
      Think of your blood pressure like the water pipes in your house:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>If pressure is too high, pipes may burst.</li>
      <li>If pressure is too low, nothing flows.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="bp-highlight">
       The right pressure keeps everything running smoothly—and keeps your heart safe.
    </p>
  </div>
